## Assembly

### Step 1

> Take the two **side panels**. Wrap masking tape along the bottom edge of each panel (this edge will sit near the wearer's shoulders and jaw — tape it for comfort).

### Step 2

> Stand the two side panels upright and parallel, 20 cm apart (the width of the top panel). Place the **top panel** across their top edges, bridging them. Tape along both joints with packing tape — two strips on the outside, one on the inside of each joint.

*You now have an open-bottomed, three-sided box.*

### Step 3

> Take the **front panel**. Position it against the front edges of the two side panels, aligned with the top. The front panel is shorter than the side panels — it leaves an opening at the bottom for the wearer's face. Tape along the left, right, and top edges.

### Step 4

> Take the two **handle tubes**. Tape one to the inside of each side panel, positioned vertically near the bottom rear corner. These act as grips the wearer can hold to stabilise the frame, and they extend the sense of the head's structure down toward the hands.

### Step 5

> Wrap masking tape along all interior edges that will be near the wearer's face and neck. Check for any sharp corners or exposed corrugation and cover them.

---

## Fit and adjust

Lower the frame over the head. The open bottom rests on the shoulders; the face is visible through the opening below the front panel. The wearer holds the handle tubes at their sides or lets them hang.

**Check:** Can the wearer breathe freely? Can they see straight ahead and downward? Can they remove the frame by lifting upward without assistance?

**Adjust:** If the frame is too narrow, widen the top panel and re-tape. If it drops too low, shorten the side panels from the bottom.

---

## Movement notes

The frame extends the perceived volume of the head outward and upward. Turning to look at something now involves rotating the entire frame, which is wider and heavier than the head alone. The wearer tends to discover whole-body turning in place of quick head swivels. Peripheral vision is partially occluded by the side panels, making the wearer more deliberate about directing attention. The handle tubes, if gripped, link the head and hands into a single kinetic unit.

---

## Design bridge

This extension foregrounds the relationship between sensory direction and body rotation — directly relevant to designing how a robot "looks at" something. A robot with no eyes or face must orient its entire body to indicate attention. The rotation speed and commitment of the whole-body turn maps to the base pan servo (C) and the upper cuboid pitch (A). The deliberateness the wearer discovers corresponds to higher `stepDelay` values.

---

## Variations

- **Deeper frame:** Extend the side panels forward to further restrict peripheral vision, forcing more dramatic whole-body reorientation.
- **Asymmetric:** Make one side panel taller than the other to create an uneven head volume — explore how asymmetry changes the quality of attention.
- **No handles:** Remove the tubes to decouple the head extension from the hands.

